<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-661-422  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 661 422.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  June 28 1990 v35 n13A pS65(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>You can't escape top-down design; in the '90s, says Morris Jones,EEs will 'orchestrate' systems rather than design them.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Greco, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Chips and Technologies Inc (San Jose, CA) co-founder, CTO andAdvanced Products VP Morris Jones believes that electronicsengineering is evolving towards an era of top-down design in whichengineers will 'orchestrate' systems.andP;  This is being propelled byadvances in sophisticated computer-aided engineering andcomputer-aided software engineering technologies, the emergence ofstandards, object-oriented programming interfaces, and greatersystems-level hardware and software integration.andP;  Engineers willhave to broaden their knowledge of engineering technologies abroadas well as develop an understanding of the market aspects of theproducts they are designing.andP;  Jones believes that most engineeringgraduates have excellent low-level skills, but that the nature ofthe industry will require engineers to continue acquiringtechnology, marketing, finance and communications skills.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chips and Technologies Inc. (officials and employees).andO;Topic:     Industry AnalysisElectronic IndustryEngineering Education.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Morris Jones. (portrait)Person:    Jones, Morris (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>